{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b9912fae-50e1-4379-8c49-e21cd1df7bf2","content":"There's no workflow file in the current directory, so I'll give you a general guide for switching from `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY` to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC).\n\n## What to change\n\n### 1. NuGet.org setup\n- Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → Your Package → Trusted Publishers**\n- Add a new **GitHub Actions** trusted publisher, specifying your repo owner, repo name, and the workflow filename/environment\n\n### 2. Workflow changes\n\n**Add permissions** to your job (or workflow level):\n\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC token\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**Replace** your `dotnet nuget push` step. Instead of:\n\n```yaml\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Use the official action** that handles the OIDC token exchange:\n\n```yaml\n- name: Push to NuGet\n  uses: dotnet/nuget-push@v1\n  with:\n    source: https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nThis action automatically requests an OIDC token from GitHub and exchanges it with NuGet.org — no API key needed.\n\n### 3. Clean up\n- Remove `NUGET_API_KEY` from your repository secrets once the new flow is verified.\n\n### Key benefits\n- **No long-lived secrets** to rotate or leak\n- **Scoped trust** — only your specific repo/workflow can publish\n- The OIDC token is short-lived and automatically managed by GitHub Actions","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ed856301-8412-4ccf-813d-9d9f3fdd68c2","outputTokens":409,"requestId":"243C:36C28E:15CEC75:1860874:6A051EAD"},"id":"57ea2a89-c72f-46c6-bc86-501cfbb83516","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:00:40.400Z","parentId":"658c921c-9224-48e3-87d9-c3f1c1288c9e"}
